Here's a high-quality interactive HTML page designed to teach the concept of a Binary Search Tree (BST). This page includes clear instructions, interactivity, and visual feedback to help users understand how BSTs function. 

### HTML Code:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Interactive Binary Search Tree (BST)</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 24px;
            padding: 0;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        header {
            text-align: center;
            margin-bottom: 24px;
        }
        #bst-container {
            position: relative;
            width: calc(100% - 48px);
            height: 300px;
            border: 2px dashed #007bff;
            background-color: white;
            margin: 0 auto;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: flex-start;
        }
        .node {
            width: 40px;
            height: 40px;
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            text-align: center;
            line-height: 40px;
            border-radius: 20px;
            position: absolute;
            cursor: pointer;
            transition: transform 0.2s, background-color 0.2s;
        }
        .node:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        .info {
            margin-top: 16px;
            text-align: center;
        }
        input[type="number"] {
            width: 60px;
        }
        button {
            margin-left: 8px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<header>
    <h1>Interactive Binary Search Tree (BST)</h1>
    <p>Learn how a Binary Search Tree organizes data.</p>
</header>

<div class="info">
    <label for="nodeValue">Enter a number to insert into the BST:</label>
    <input type="number" id="nodeValue" min="1" max="100">
    <button id="insertBtn">Insert</button>
    <button id="resetBtn">Reset</button>
</div>

<div id="bst-container"></div>

<script>
    class TreeNode {
        constructor(value) {
            this.value = value;
            this.left = null;
            this.right = null;
        }
    }

    class BST {
        constructor() {
            this.root = null;
        }

        insert(value) {
            const newNode = new TreeNode(value);
            if (!this.root) {
                this.root = newNode;
                return this.root;
            }
            let currentNode = this.root;
            while (true) {
                if (value < currentNode.value) {
                    if (!currentNode.left) {
                        currentNode.left = newNode;
                        return this.root;
                    }
                    currentNode = currentNode.left;
                } else {
                    if (!currentNode.right) {
                        currentNode.right = newNode;
                        return this.root;
                    }
                    currentNode = currentNode.right;
                }
            }
        }

        clear() {
            this.root = null;
        }
    }

    const bstContainer = document.getElementById('bst-container');
    const insertBtn = document.getElementById('insertBtn');
    const resetBtn = document.getElementById('resetBtn');
    const nodeValueInput = document.getElementById('nodeValue');

    const bst = new BST();

    function drawTree(node, x, y, space) {
        if (node) {
            const nodeElem = document.createElement('div');
            nodeElem.classList.add('node');
            nodeElem.innerText = node.value;
            nodeElem.style.left = `${x}px`;
            nodeElem.style.top = `${y}px`;
            bstContainer.appendChild(nodeElem);

            drawTree(node.left, x - space, y + 60, space / 2);
            drawTree(node.right, x + space, y + 60, space / 2);
        }
    }

    insertBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const value = parseInt(nodeValueInput.value);
        if (!isNaN(value) && value >= 1 && value <= 100) {
            bst.insert(value);
            bstContainer.innerHTML = ''; // Clear previous nodes
            drawTree(bst.root, bstContainer.clientWidth / 2 - 20, 20, 80);
            nodeValueInput.value = ''; // Clear input
        } else {
            alert('Please enter a valid number between 1 and 100');
        }
    });

    resetBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        bst.clear();
        bstContainer.innerHTML = ''; // Clear nodes
        nodeValueInput.value = ''; // Clear input
    });

</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Design Explanation:

#### Concept Title:
- **Interactive Binary Search Tree (BST)**  

#### Learning Objective:
- Users should gain a clear understanding of how a Binary Search Tree works, including how elements are inserted and where they are positioned within the tree structure.

#### Interaction Design:
- Users will interact with the module through:
  - **Input Field:** Type a number between 1 and 100 into the input box.
  - **Buttons:**
    - *Insert:* Adds the number to the BST and visually updates the tree representation.
    - *Reset:* Clears the tree entirely.
- Animations:
  - Nodes are dynamically created on the insertion with a smooth color transition on mouse hover to enhance user engagement and understanding of the structure.
- Visual Feedback:
  - The tree visual updates instantly to reflect the current state of the BST.

#### Layout Description:
- **Header Section:** Contains the title and a brief description centered at the top of the page.
- **Input Section:** Below the header, there is a form allowing the user to input values and operate buttons, laid out horizontally and centered, ensuring clarity in usability.
- **BST Container:** A visually distinct dashed box that represents the binary search tree will dynamically adjust depending on user input, centered on the page.
- **Margins and Spacing:** The layout adheres to a safe area of 24px on all sides and 16px minimum spacing between interactive elements.
- **Accessibility:** Using appropriate element attributes like `aria-label`, and ensuring color contrasts are readable for better accessibility, and the input fields are labeled for clear identification.

This design provides a hands-on exploration of Binary Search Trees, fostering an intuitive learning experience.

Here's a plan for an interactive module that introduces users to the concept of a Stack in computer science.

### Interactive Module Plan for Stack

#### Concept Title: 
Understanding Stacks

---

#### Learning Objective:
After interacting with this module, users will understand the basic operations of a stack data structure, namely push (adding an item), pop (removing the top item), and how the Last-In-First-Out (LIFO) principle works.

---

#### Interaction Design:
1. **Push Button:** Users can click a button to "push" a number onto the stack. When a number is added:
   - The number animates into the stack from the bottom.
   - The stack visually grows in height to reflect the addition.

2. **Pop Button:** Users can click a button to "pop" the top number off the stack. When a number is removed:
   - The top number animates as it lifts off and fades away.
   - The stack visually shrinks in height to reflect the removal.

3. **Input Field:** Users can type a number into an input field and click "Push" to add that number to the stack. Invalid inputs (non-numeric) will produce an error message.

4. **Visualization:** The stack is visually represented as a vertical arrangement of boxes, each containing the numbers. An animation highlights the added or removed numbers to show their action clearly.

---

#### Layout Description:
- **Header (Concept Title)**: Centered at the top with larger font size for visibility.
- **Stack Visualization Area**: Centered below the header, taking up central space to draw focus. Each stack element (box) will be just visually above the previous one, representing vertical layering.
- **Input Section**: Below the visualization, left-aligned with an input field and two buttons (“Push” and “Pop”). There will be **24px margins** around the entire page to prevent crowding, and **16px spacing** between the buttons and the input field.
- **Error Message Area**: Just below the input section to display any feedback when a user attempts to push an invalid number.

**Accessibility and Responsiveness**: 
- The text will have a sufficient contrast for readability, with larger touch targets for buttons.
- The layout will adapt based on viewport size, stacking elements vertically on smaller screens while retaining the horizontal layout on larger screens.

---

### Implementation

