            <div class="cell" data-row="2" data-col="0"></div>
            <div class="cell" data-row="2" data-col="1"></div>
            <div class="cell" data-row="2" data-col="2"></div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="controls">
        <label for="new-value">Enter Value (0 or 1):</label>
        <input type="number" id="new-value" min="0" max="1" />
        <button id="apply-button">Apply Value</button>
    </div>

    <div class="result" id="result-display"></div>

    <script>
        const cells = document.querySelectorAll('.cell');
        const applyButton = document.getElementById('apply-button');
        const newValueInput = document.getElementById('new-value');
        const resultDisplay = document.getElementById('result-display');

        cells.forEach(cell => {
            cell.addEventListener('click', () => {
                cell.classList.toggle('active');
                updateResult();
            });
        });

        applyButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
            const value = parseInt(newValueInput.value);
            if (value !== 0 && value !== 1) {
                alert('Please enter 0 or 1.');
                return;
            }
            const activeCells = document.querySelectorAll('.cell.active');
            activeCells.forEach(cell => {
                cell.textContent = value;
            });
            newValueInput.value = ''; // clear input
            updateResult();
        });

        function updateResult() {
            const matrix = Array.from({ length: 3 }, () => Array(3).fill(0));
            cells.forEach(cell => {
                const row = cell.dataset.row;
                const col = cell.dataset.col;
                if (cell.classList.contains('active')) {
                    matrix[row][col] = cell.textContent ? parseInt(cell.textContent) : 1; // default to 1
                }
            });
            resultDisplay.textContent = 'Adjacency Matrix: ' + JSON.stringify(matrix);
        }
    </script>

</body>

</html>
```

### Explanation of the Design:

1. **Concept Title**: "Exploring Adjacency Matrix" clearly introduces the topic to the user.

2. **Learning Objective**: Users will learn how graphs can be represented through adjacency matrices with hands-on interaction.

3. **Interaction Design**:
   - Users can click on the cells of the matrix to select them. Selected cells are highlighted to indicate they are part of the adjacency relation.
   - Users can input either `0` or `1` into a number input field, which indicates whether an edge exists between the corresponding nodes.
   - When the "Apply Value" button is clicked, selected cells will display the value based on user input.
   - The final adjacency matrix will be displayed in a results area so users can visually see the outcome of their changes, enhancing the learning experience.

4. **Layout Description**:
   - The layout keeps a clear column arrangement with ample spacing between elements to avoid clutter. 
   - The matrix occupies the center of the module, while controls and results follow logically below.
   - This organization ensures a visually pleasing and focused interaction, complying with the stated safe areas and spacing requirements.

The provided interactive HTML page meets all requirements, allowing users to learn by engaging directly with the concept of adjacency matrices.

