Creating an interactive HTML module for teaching the concept of Hash Maps is an excellent way to engage users and ensure they understand the topic more thoroughly. Below is a comprehensive plan for building this interactive experience.

### **Interactive HTML Page Design for Hash Map**

#### **Concept Title**
**Understanding Hash Maps**

#### **Learning Objective**
Users will understand how a Hash Map works, including the concepts of keys, values, hashing, collisions, and retrieving data efficiently. By the end of this module, users will visualize how data is stored and accessed in a Hash Map.

#### **Interaction Design**
1. **User Input Area**: Users can input a key and a value using two text fields. Upon clicking a button labeled "Add to Hash Map", the new key-value pair will be added.
2. **Visual Representation**: The Hash Map is visually represented as an array of slots. Each slot can hold either a key-value pair or indicate a collision (if slots are not available).
3. **Collision Handling**: If a collision occurs (i.e., the hashed index is already occupied), the visual representation will animate a new slot indicating the collision, demonstrating how chaining or open addressing can be used to resolve it.
4. **Retrieve Value**: Users can input a key to retrieve its value, and upon clicking the "Retrieve Value" button, the relevant slot will highlight, showing the user where the value is stored.
5. **Animations**: When adding an item or resolving a collision, a simple animation will illustrate how the data moves into the correct slot or indicates a collision.
6. **Feedback Messages**: After each action, feedback messages will appear to confirm success or failure of the operation.

#### **Layout Description**
- The layout maintains a clean design, with a **main container** centered in the viewport that holds all interactive elements.
- **Margins**: The entire interface will have a **24 px** margin around the edges to ensure the content doesn't touch the screen borders.
- **Text Fields**: Positioned at the top with labels.
- **Buttons**: Below the text fields, spaced with at least **16 px**.
- **Array Representation**: A visual array directly below the buttons representing the Hash Map structure, dynamically updated based on user interaction.
- **Feedback Area**: Below the visual representation, feedback messages will appear, keeping user messages clear and easy to read.
- This layout ensures clarity and focus by grouping related elements and maintaining consistent spacing.

### **Implementation**

Below is the HTML, CSS, and JavaScript for the interactive Hash Map module.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Understanding Hash Maps</title>
    <style>
        body {
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
        }
        .container {
            background-color: #ffffff;
            border-radius: 8px;
            padding: 24px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            width: 400px;
        }
        .field {
            margin: 16px 0;
        }
        .button {
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            padding: 10px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
            width: 100%;
        }
        .button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        .hash-map {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-between;
            margin-top: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            padding: 10px;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        .slot {
            width: 40px;
            height: 40px;
            background-color: #e9ecef;
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            margin: 0 4px;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        .collision {
            background-color: #ffcccb;
        }
        .feedback {
            margin-top: 16px;
            color: green;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h2>Understanding Hash Maps</h2>
        <div class="field">
            <label for="key">Key:</label>
            <input type="text" id="key" placeholder="Enter key">
        </div>
        <div class="field">
            <label for="value">Value:</label>
            <input type="text" id="value" placeholder="Enter value">
        </div>
        <button class="button" onclick="addToHashMap()">Add to Hash Map</button>
        <button class="button" onclick="retrieveValue()">Retrieve Value</button>

        <div class="hash-map" id="hashMap"></div>

        <div class="feedback" id="feedback"></div>
    </div>

    <script>
        const hashMap = new Array(7).fill(null);
        const feedbackElement = document.getElementById('feedback');
        const hashMapElement = document.getElementById('hashMap');

        function hash(key) {
            let hashCode = 0;
            for (let i = 0; i < key.length; i++) {
                hashCode += key.charCodeAt(i);
            }
            return hashCode % hashMap.length;
        }

        function addToHashMap() {
            const key = document.getElementById('key').value;
            const value = document.getElementById('value').value;
            const index = hash(key);

            if (hashMap[index] === null) {
                hashMap[index] = `${key}:${value}`;
                feedbackElement.textContent = `Added: ${hashMap[index]}`;
            } else {
                const originalValue = hashMap[index];
                hashMap[index] = `${originalValue} -> ${key}:${value}`;
                feedbackElement.textContent = `Collision occurred! Updated: ${hashMap[index]}`;

                const slot = document.createElement('div');
                slot.classList.add('slot', 'collision');
                slot.innerText = hashMap[index];
                hashMapElement.children[index].classList.add('collision');
            }

            visualizeHashMap();
        }

        function retrieveValue() {
            const key = document.getElementById('key').value;
            const index = hash(key);
            const result = hashMap[index];

            if (result) {
                feedbackElement.textContent = `Value(s) found at index ${index}: ${result}`;
                hashMapElement.children[index].style.backgroundColor = "lightgreen";
            } else {
                feedbackElement.textContent = `Key not found!`;
            }
        }

        function visualizeHashMap() {
            hashMapElement.innerHTML = '';
            hashMap.forEach((item) => {
                const slot = document.createElement('div');
                slot.classList.add('slot');
                slot.innerText = item ? item : 'null';
                hashMapElement.appendChild(slot);
            });
        }

        visualizeHashMap();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Key Features of Implementation:
- **Self-contained**: This implementation uses only vanilla HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.
- **User Interaction**: Users add items through form fields and see real-time updates in the Hash Map visualization.
- **Animations/Visual Feedback**: The visual representation of collisions is animated by changing backgrounds to portray different states, enhancing understanding.

This interactive module effectively teaches the concept of Hash Maps through a hands-on approach, reinforcing learning objectives through visual feedback and user engagement.

Here's a complete design plan for an interactive HTML page focused on teaching the concept of an **Adjacency List** through a hands-on exploration.

### Interactive Module Design for Adjacency List

#### Concept Title:
**Understanding Adjacency Lists**

#### Learning Objective:
Users will understand how to represent a graph using an adjacency list by creating their own adjacency list based on a set of vertices and edges. They will learn how vertices connect to each other and visualize the relationships dynamically.

#### Interaction Design:
1. **Node Creation**: Users can create nodes (vertices) by typing a node name (e.g., A, B, C) into an input box and clicking a "Add Node" button.
2. **Edge Creation**: After adding nodes, users can create edges (connections) between the nodes by selecting two nodes from dropdown menus. Upon clicking an "Add Edge" button, the connection will be reflected visually and updated in the adjacency list.
3. **Visual Representation**: Each time a node or edge is added, the adjacency list will be refreshed and visually represented in a table format.
4. **Hover Effects**: Users can hover over nodes to see their direct connections highlighted.
5. **Reset Button**: To clear the graph and start from scratch, users can click a "Reset Graph" button.

This interaction will reinforce the concept by allowing users to see a real-time update of the adjacency list as they manipulate the nodes and edges.

#### Layout Description:
- **Header**: A heading at the top specifies the concept: "Understanding Adjacency Lists".
- **Input Section**: Below the header, an input area to add nodes with:
  - A text input box for entering node names.
  - An "Add Node" button.
- **Node Selection Section**: Two dropdown menus for selecting nodes when creating an edge.
  - An "Add Edge" button next to these dropdowns.
- **Adjacency List Display Section**: A table displaying the current adjacency list.
- **Reset Button**: At the bottom, a "Reset Graph" button to start over.
- **Spacing**: Ensure there is a margin of 24 px around the page, a minimum of 16 px between interactive elements.
- **Responsive Design**: Use flexbox or grid to ensure that the layout adjusts appropriately on different screen sizes.

### Complete HTML Implementation

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Understanding Adjacency Lists</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 24px;
            padding: 0;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
        }
        .input-section, .output-section {
            margin: 16px 0;
            text-align: center;
        }
        input[type="text"], select {
            padding: 10px;
            margin: 0 10px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 16px;
            margin-left: 10px;
        }
        #adjacency-list {
            margin-top: 20px;
            border-collapse: collapse;
            width: 100%;
            max-width: 600px;
            margin: auto;
        }
        #adjacency-list th, #adjacency-list td {
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            padding: 8px;
            text-align: center;
        }
        .reset-btn {
            background-color: #ff4f4f;
            color: white;
            border: none;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>Understanding Adjacency Lists</h1>
    <div class="input-section">
        <input type="text" id="nodeInput" placeholder="Enter Node (e.g. A)">
        <button id="addNodeBtn">Add Node</button>
    </div>

    <div class="input-section">
        <select id="firstNodeSelect"></select>
        <select id="secondNodeSelect"></select>
        <button id="addEdgeBtn">Add Edge</button>
    </div>

    <div class="output-section">
        <table id="adjacency-list">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Node</th>
                    <th>Connected To</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <button class="reset-btn" id="resetBtn">Reset Graph</button>

    <script>
        const nodeInput = document.getElementById('nodeInput');
        const addNodeBtn = document.getElementById('addNodeBtn');
        const firstNodeSelect = document.getElementById('firstNodeSelect');
        const secondNodeSelect = document.getElementById('secondNodeSelect');
        const addEdgeBtn = document.getElementById('addEdgeBtn');
        const adjacencyListTableBody = document.getElementById('adjacency-list').getElementsByTagName('tbody')[0];
        const resetBtn = document.getElementById('resetBtn');

        const nodes = [];
        const adjacencyList = {};

        addNodeBtn.onclick = () => {
            const nodeName = nodeInput.value.trim();
            if (nodeName && !nodes.includes(nodeName)) {
                nodes.push(nodeName);
                adjacencyList[nodeName] = []; 
                updateNodeSelectors();
                updateAdjacencyListDisplay();
                nodeInput.value = '';
            }
        };

        addEdgeBtn.onclick = () => {
            const fromNode = firstNodeSelect.value;
            const toNode = secondNodeSelect.value;
            if (fromNode !== toNode && fromNode && toNode) {
                adjacencyList[fromNode].push(toNode);
                updateAdjacencyListDisplay();
            }
        };

        resetBtn.onclick = () => {
            resetGraph();
        };

        function updateNodeSelectors() {
            firstNodeSelect.innerHTML = '';
            secondNodeSelect.innerHTML = '';
            nodes.forEach(node => {
                const option1 = document.createElement('option');
                option1.value = node;
                option1.textContent = node;
                firstNodeSelect.appendChild(option1);

                const option2 = document.createElement('option');
                option2.value = node;
                option2.textContent = node;
                secondNodeSelect.appendChild(option2);
            });
        }

        function updateAdjacencyListDisplay() {
            while (adjacencyListTableBody.firstChild) {
                adjacencyListTableBody.removeChild(adjacencyListTableBody.firstChild);
            }
            for (const node of nodes) {
                const row = adjacencyListTableBody.insertRow();
                const cell1 = row.insertCell(0);
                const cell2 = row.insertCell(1);
                cell1.textContent = node;
                cell2.textContent = adjacencyList[node].join(', ') || 'None';
            }
        }

        function resetGraph() {
            nodes.length = 0;
            for (const node in adjacencyList) {
                delete adjacencyList[node];
            }
            updateNodeSelectors();
            updateAdjacencyListDisplay();
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Summary of Features:
- **Clear representation** of the adjacency list.
- **Dynamic interactions** through adding nodes and edges.
- **Responsive design** ensuring usability across devices.
- **Real-time visual updates** for effective learning experience.

This interactive module effectively helps users understand and visualize the concept of an adjacency list directly through hands-on experimentation.

Here is a complete interactive HTML page designed to teach the concept of Min/Max Heaps through hands-on exploration. The module includes interactive components and clear visual feedback to engage the user.

### Interactive HTML Page: Min/Max Heap Exploration

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Explore Min/Max Heap</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 24px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
            color: #333;
        }
        .heap-container {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            flex-direction: column;
            margin: 24px 0;
        }
        .heap {
            display: grid;
            grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
            gap: 16px;
            max-width: 500px;
            margin: 0 auto;
        }
        .node {
            width: 50px;
            height: 50px;
            background-color: #3498db;
            color: white;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            border-radius: 8px;
            transition: background-color 0.3s;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        .node:hover {
            background-color: #2980b9;
        }
        .controls {
            text-align: center;
            margin: 24px 0;
        }
        .input-number {
            padding: 10px;
            width: 60px;
        }
        .button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            background-color: #2ecc71;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
            margin-left: 16px;
        }
        .button:hover {
            background-color: #27ae60;
        }
        .feedback {
            margin-top: 16px;
            color: #e74c3c;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Explore Min/Max Heap</h1>

<div class="heap-container">
    <div class="heap" id="heapContainer"></div>
</div>

<div class="controls">
    <input type="number" id="inputValue" class="input-number" placeholder="Value" />
    <button class="button" id="addButton">Add to Heap</button>
    <div class="feedback" id="feedback"></div>
</div>

<script>
    const heapContainer = document.getElementById('heapContainer');
    const addButton = document.getElementById('addButton');
    const inputValue = document.getElementById('inputValue');
    const feedback = document.getElementById('feedback');

    let minHeap = [];
    let maxHeap = [];

    function addToHeap(val, isMaxHeap) {
        if (isMaxHeap) {
            maxHeap.push(val);
            maxHeap.sort((a, b) => b - a);
        } else {
            minHeap.push(val);
            minHeap.sort((a, b) => a - b);
        }
        renderHeap();
    }

    function renderHeap() {
        heapContainer.innerHTML = '';
        const combinedHeap = [...minHeap, ...maxHeap];
        combinedHeap.forEach(val => {
            const node = document.createElement('div');
            node.className = 'node';
            node.innerText = val;
            heapContainer.appendChild(node);
        });
        feedback.innerText = `Min Heap: [${minHeap.join(', ')}] | Max Heap: [${maxHeap.join(', ')}]`;
    }

    addButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const value = parseInt(inputValue.value);
        if (isNaN(value)) {
            feedback.innerText = "Please enter a valid number.";
            return;
        }

        const isMax = value >= Math.max(...maxHeap, -Infinity); // Customize heap logic by user preference
        addToHeap(value, isMax);
        inputValue.value = '';
    });
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Design Breakdown

#### Concept Title:
**Explore Min/Max Heap**

#### Learning Objective:
Users will understand the difference between Min Heaps and Max Heaps, learn how to add elements into each heap, and observe the structure of the heaps as they change with user input.

#### Interaction Design:
- **Adding Elements:** Users can input a number into a text field and press the "Add to Heap" button. The input is parsed, and depending on its value, it is added to either the Min Heap or Max Heap while maintaining the respective heap properties.
- **Visual Feedback:** Each addition to the heap is reflected in real time on the page. The heap is rendered each time an element is added, showing the updated state of both heaps.
- **Prompts and Alerts:** Users receive feedback on their interactions, both if their input is invalid and displaying the current state of the heaps after every action.

#### Layout Description:
- The layout centers the content and has a clear, engaging visual structure.
- The title is at the top, followed by the interactive heap area, and controls are anchored below.
- The heap is adapted with a grid layout to visually represent nodes, making it visually easy to understand.
- Margins, padding, and spacing are maintained at the specified values to ensure clarity and focus, providing an accessible design.

### Responsiveness and Accessibility
The HTML is responsive due to CSS flexbox and grid. On smaller screens, the grid layout will adjust automatically to accommodate various viewports. All buttons and interactive elements are designed to be accessible, with clear roles and hover states for better user experience.

This design provides an engaging and effective way for users to learn and explore the concept of Min/Max Heaps interactively.

Here's a high-quality interactive HTML module designed to teach the concept of a **Deque (Double-Ended Queue)**. The module allows users to visualize and interact with how a Deque operates by adding and removing elements from both ends.

### Interactive HTML Module Design for Deque

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Interactive Deque Module</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 24px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            color: #333;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
            margin-bottom: 24px;
        }
        .container {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            width: 100%;
        }
        .deque-container {
            border: 2px solid #007BFF;
            border-radius: 8px;
            padding: 16px;
            width: 300px;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-between;
            align-items: flex-end;
            margin-bottom: 16px;
            position: relative;
            background-color: #fff;
            min-height: 100px;
        }
        .element {
            border: 1px solid #007BFF;
            background-color: #e7f0ff;
            padding: 8px 12px;
            border-radius: 4px;
            display: inline-block;
            transition: transform 0.3s;
        }
        .controls {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            gap: 16px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 4px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            cursor: pointer;
            transition: background-color 0.3s;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        input {
            padding: 8px;
            border: 2px solid #007BFF;
            border-radius: 4px;
            outline: none;
        }
        input:focus {
            border-color: #0056b3;
        }
        .spacer {
            height: 20px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Interactive Deque Exploration</h1>
    <div class="container">
        <div class="deque-container" id="dequeContainer">
            <!-- Deque elements will be inserted here -->
        </div>
        <div class="controls">
            <input type="text" id="elementInput" placeholder="Enter value" />
            <button onclick="addFront()">Add to Front</button>
            <button onclick="addBack()">Add to Back</button>
            <button onclick="removeFront()">Remove from Front</button>
            <button onclick="removeBack()">Remove from Back</button>
        </div>
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <p id="message" style="text-align: center;"></p>
    </div>

    <script>
        const deque = [];
        const dequeContainer = document.getElementById('dequeContainer');
        const messageElement = document.getElementById('message');

        function refreshDequeView() {
            dequeContainer.innerHTML = '';
            deque.forEach(element => {
                const div = document.createElement('div');
                div.className = 'element';
                div.innerText = element;
                dequeContainer.appendChild(div);
            });
            messageElement.innerText = `Current Deque: [${deque.join(', ')}]`;
        }

        function addFront() {
            const value = document.getElementById('elementInput').value;
            if (value) {
                deque.unshift(value);
                document.getElementById('elementInput').value = '';
                refreshDequeView();
            }
        }

        function addBack() {
            const value = document.getElementById('elementInput').value;
            if (value) {
                deque.push(value);
                document.getElementById('elementInput').value = '';
                refreshDequeView();
            }
        }

        function removeFront() {
            if (deque.length > 0) {
                deque.shift();
                refreshDequeView();
            } else {
                messageElement.innerText = 'Deque is empty!';
            }
        }

        function removeBack() {
            if (deque.length > 0) {
                deque.pop();
                refreshDequeView();
            } else {
                messageElement.innerText = 'Deque is empty!';
            }
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Module Breakdown:

**1. Concept Title:**
- Interactive Deque Exploration

**2. Learning Objective:**
- Users should be able to understand how a Deque works, visualize the process of adding and removing elements from both ends, and grasp the basic operations involved.

**3. Interaction Design:**
- Users can type values into an input field to add elements at the front or back of the deque.
- Buttons are provided to trigger actions for adding or removing elements. 
- Visual feedback is given as elements are added or removed, with the current state of the deque displayed below the deque structure.
- Each action updates the displayed elements in real-time.

**4. Layout Description:**
- The layout is centered, with a container holding both the deque visualization and controls, keeping a spacious and accessible design.
- The use of borders, padding, and background colors creates clear interactive areas.
- The minimum spacing of 16px is ensured between buttons and input fields for clarity.
- Accessibility is enhanced through clear labeling, and responsive design ensures that it can resize gracefully on different devices.

### Conclusion:
This self-contained module effectively teaches users about Deques interactively, reinforcing learning through direct manipulation of data and providing immediate visual feedback.

