  - **Header Section:** At the very top, centered, with the title "Exploring Adjacency Lists."
  - **Input Area:** Below the title, with a space to input node names, an "Add Node" button, and a text area displaying the adjacency list. This ensures that users can easily add nodes and see immediate feedback.
  - **Graph Visualization Area:** Below the input area, spanning most of the width of the interface where nodes and edges dynamically appear; this area should have a light background to contrast with nodes and lines.
  - **Reset Button:** Positioned below the graph area, centered, and clearly labeled to ensure users can quickly clear their current state.

- **Accessibility and Responsiveness:** 
  - All interactive elements are large enough for easy clicking (at least 44px by 44px).
  - The layout flexbox ensures responsiveness across different devices while maintaining the specified margins.

---

### Example Code Implementation:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Exploring Adjacency Lists</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 24px;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
        }
        h1 {
            margin-bottom: 16px;
        }
        #inputArea {
            margin-bottom: 16px;
        }
        input, button {
            padding: 8px;
            margin-right: 8px;
        }
        #graphArea {
            width: 100%;
            height: 300px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            position: relative;
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
        }
        #adjacencyList {
            margin-top: 16px;
            width: 100%;
            max-width: 300px;
            height: 200px;
            overflow-y: auto;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            padding: 8px;
            background-color: #fff;
        }
        .node {
            width: 30px;
            height: 30px;
            border-radius: 50%;
            background-color: #007bff;
            position: absolute;
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            color: white;
            font-size: 16px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        .selected {
            background-color: #ff6b6b;
        }
        .line {
            position: absolute;
            background-color: black;
            transition: 0.5s;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Exploring Adjacency Lists</h1>
    <div id="inputArea">
        <input type="text" id="nodeInput" placeholder="Enter node name" />
        <button id="addNodeBtn">Add Node</button>
    </div>
    <div id="graphArea"></div>
    <div id="adjacencyList"></div>
    <button id="resetBtn" style="margin-top: 16px;">Reset Graph</button>

    <script>
        let nodes = [];
        let edges = [];
        let selectedNode = null;

        const graphArea = document.getElementById('graphArea');
        const adjacencyList = document.getElementById('adjacencyList');
        const resetBtn = document.getElementById('resetBtn');
        const addNodeBtn = document.getElementById('addNodeBtn');
        const nodeInput = document.getElementById('nodeInput');

        const updateAdjacencyList = () => {
            adjacencyList.innerHTML = JSON.stringify(edges, null, 2);
        };

        const drawLine = (x1, y1, x2, y2) => {
            const line = document.createElement('div');
            line.classList.add('line');
            const length = Math.sqrt((x2 - x1) ** 2 + (y2 - y1) ** 2);
            line.style.width = `${length}px`;
            line.style.transform = `rotate(${Math.atan2(y2 - y1, x2 - x1)}rad)`;
            line.style.left = `${x1}px`;
            line.style.top = `${y1}px`;
            graphArea.appendChild(line);
            setTimeout(() => {
                line.style.transition = 'none';
                line.style.width = '0';
            }, 500);
        };

        addNodeBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
            const name = nodeInput.value.trim();
            if (name) {
                const nodeElement = document.createElement('div');
                const x = Math.random() * (graphArea.clientWidth - 30);
                const y = Math.random() * (graphArea.clientHeight - 30);
                nodeElement.className = 'node';
                nodeElement.style.left = `${x}px`;
                nodeElement.style.top = `${y}px`;
                nodeElement.innerText = name;
                nodeElement.addEventListener('click', () => {
                    if (selectedNode === nodeElement) {
                        nodeElement.classList.remove('selected');
                        selectedNode = null;
                    } else {
                        if (selectedNode) {
                            const srcNode = selectedNode.innerText;
                            const destNode = nodeElement.innerText;
                            edges.push([srcNode, destNode]);
                            drawLine(selectedNode.offsetLeft + 15, selectedNode.offsetTop + 15,
                                      nodeElement.offsetLeft + 15, nodeElement.offsetTop + 15);
                            updateAdjacencyList();
                            selectedNode.classList.remove('selected');
                        }
                        selectedNode = nodeElement;
                        selectedNode.classList.add('selected');
                    }
                });
                graphArea.appendChild(nodeElement);
                nodes.push(name);
                nodeInput.value = '';
                updateAdjacencyList();
            }
        });

        resetBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
            nodes = [];
            edges = [];
            selectedNode = null;
            graphArea.innerHTML = '';
            adjacencyList.innerHTML = '';
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation of the Code:
1. **HTML Structure:** The page contains a header for the title, input controls for adding nodes, a div for graph visualization, and a reset button. 
2. **CSS:** Styles define the layout, visual aspects of nodes, and edges with distinct colors and transition effects for animations.
3. **JavaScript:** 
   - Manages the addition of nodes and edges, captures user interactions, and updates the adjacency list.
   - Draws visual lines between nodes dynamically and provides user feedback through color changes.
   - Resets the state effectively when needed.

This interactive module provides a hands-on learning experience that effectively illustrates the concept of adjacency lists in a clear and engaging manner.

Below is a detailed design plan for an interactive HTML page that effectively teaches the concept of a Queue. This module encourages hands-on exploration through user interaction.

### Interactive HTML Page: Queue

#### Concept Title
**Understanding Queues: FIFO Data Structure**

#### Learning Objective
By interacting with this module, users will understand the FIFO (First In, First Out) principle of queues, how elements are added and removed, and visualize the operations through animations.

#### Interaction Design
1. **User Interactions:**
   - **Enqueue Button:** When the user clicks the "Enqueue" button, they can input a number in a text box. Upon pressing "Add," the number is added to the queue.
   - **Dequeue Button:** Clicking the "Dequeue" button removes the front element from the queue and visually transitions it out.
   - **Visual Representation:** The queue will be displayed as a horizontal bar (like a waiting line), where each element is represented by a rectangular box. Animations will be used to illustrate the addition and removal of elements.
   - **Feedback Tips:** Tooltips will appear briefly to provide feedback on what is happening (e.g., "Added: x" or "Removed: y").

2. **State Changes:**
   - The queue representation updates dynamically; when an item is added, the new box appears at the end, shifting earlier items left. When an item is removed, it animates moving out and disappears.

3. **Animation Effects:**
   - Smooth transitions will be used during enqueuing and dequeuing processes, enhancing user understanding through visual cues.

#### Layout Description
- **Overall Layout:**
  - The page will have a vertical orientation with clearly defined sections to maintain clarity and balance.
- **Header Area:** 
  - Top header (24px from top) featuring the title, centered and with a larger font.
- **Queue Representation Area:** 
  - Directly below the header, a horizontal area (minimum height of 100px) for visual representation of the queue. Each element will be represented by a box with a minimum width of 30px and a height of 50px. This area will have a clear background color contrasting the boxes.
- **Controls Section:**
  - Below the queue representation, there will be two buttons: "Enqueue" and "Dequeue," spaced 16px apart. 
  - An input text box (with placeholder text "Enter a number") will be on the left side of the "Enqueue" button to allow the user to enter values.
- **Information Section:**
  - A small area at the bottom of the page for feedback messages (e.g., "Queue is now empty," or "Queue has elements.").

### Self-Contained HTML, CSS, and JavaScript Example

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Queue Interactive Module</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 24px;
            background-color: #f8f9fa;
            color: #333;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
        }
        #queue {
            display: flex;
            align-items: flex-end;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100px;
            border: 2px solid #007bff;
