   - Upon confirmation, an animation visually connects the new node in the list.

3. **Deletion Operation**:
   - Each node will have a "Delete" button.
   - Once clicked, the node visually disappears with a smooth fading animation, and the link between remaining nodes updates correspondingly.

4. **Visualization of Operations**:
   - Each operational change (creating, inserting, deleting nodes) will include animations that demonstrate the linking and unlinking of nodes.

---

#### Layout Description:
- **Overall Structure**:
  - The page is divided into three primary sections: Concept Title at the top, an Interactive Area in the center, and a Controls Area at the bottom.

- **Styling and Spacing**:
  - Safe area margins: 24 px on all sides.
  - Minimum spacing: 16 px between all interactive elements (buttons, inputs).

- **Sections Layout**:
  1. **Concept Title**: 
     - Centered at the top with a large, bold font.

  2. **Interactive Area**: 
     - This central area will hold the visual representation of the linked list, with spaced nodes appearing horizontally. It will use rectangles to represent nodes, each labeled with its content.
     - The links between nodes will be represented by lines drawn between them.

  3. **Controls Area**: 
     - Below the interactive area, there are controls: "Create Node," "Insert After," and deletion buttons for each node.
     - A text input for node data will be placed next to the "Create Node" button.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Understanding Linked Lists</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 24px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        #title {
            text-align: center;
            font-size: 2em;
            margin-bottom: 16px;
        }
        #linkedListContainer {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            margin-bottom: 24px;
            position: relative;
        }
        .node {
            width: 100px;
            height: 40px;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            border-radius: 5px;
            text-align: center;
            line-height: 40px;
            position: relative;
            margin: 0 8px; /* equal spacing */
        }
        .deleteBtn {
            position: absolute;
            top: 50%;
            right: 5px;
            transform: translateY(-50%);
            cursor: pointer;
            background-color: #f44336;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            padding: 2px 5px;
            border-radius: 3px;
        }
        #controls {
            text-align: center;
        }
        input[type='text'] {
            padding: 5px;
            margin-right: 8px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 5px 10px;
            margin: 0 8px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="title">Understanding Linked Lists</div>
    <div id="linkedListContainer"></div>
    <div id="controls">
        <input type="text" id="nodeValue" placeholder="Node value" />
        <button id="createNodeBtn">Create Node</button>
        <button id="insertAfterBtn">Insert After</button>
    </div>
    <script>
        const linkedListContainer = document.getElementById('linkedListContainer');
        const createNodeBtn = document.getElementById('createNodeBtn');
        const insertAfterBtn = document.getElementById('insertAfterBtn');
        const nodeValueInput = document.getElementById('nodeValue');

        let nodes = [];

        createNodeBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
            const value = nodeValueInput.value;
            if (value) {
                const node = createNode(value);
                linkedListContainer.appendChild(node);
                nodes.push(node);
                nodeValueInput.value = '';
            }
        });

        insertAfterBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
            const value = nodeValueInput.value;
            const index = prompt("Enter index to insert after:");
            if (value && index >= 0 && index < nodes.length) {
                const node = createNode(value);
                const nextNode = nodes[index + 1];
                linkedListContainer.insertBefore(node, nextNode);
                nodes.splice(index + 1, 0, node); // Insert in array
                nodeValueInput.value = '';
            }
        });

        function createNode(value) {
            const node = document.createElement('div');
            node.classList.add('node');
            node.innerText = value;

            const deleteBtn = document.createElement('button');
            deleteBtn.innerText = 'X';
            deleteBtn.classList.add('deleteBtn');
            deleteBtn.onclick = () => {
                node.remove();
                nodes.splice(nodes.indexOf(node), 1); // Remove from array
            };
            node.appendChild(deleteBtn);

            return node;
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Summary:
This module creates an interactive learning environment for understanding linked lists. The clean design, engaging interactions, and visual feedback will effectively convey the concept of linked nodes and related operations, allowing users to learn by doing.

Here’s a detailed design for an interactive HTML page to explore the concept of Binary Search Trees (BST). 

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Interactive Binary Search Tree</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 24px;
            background-color: #f8f9fa;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
            margin-bottom: 24px;
        }
        #learning-objective {
