            flex-direction: column-reverse;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: flex-end;
            padding: 8px;
            position: relative;
        }
        .item {
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            padding: 8px 12px;
            margin: 4px 0;
            border-radius: 5px;
            transition: transform 0.3s;
        }
        #controlPanel {
            display: flex;
            gap: 16px;
            justify-content: center;
        }
        input[type="number"] {
            width: 60px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 8px 16px;
            cursor: pointer;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            background-color: #28a745;
            color: white;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #218838;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Understand Priority Queue</h1>
        <p><strong>Learning Objective:</strong> Users will learn how a priority queue operates, how items are added based on priority levels, and how the highest priority item is removed first.</p>

        <div id="queueContainer">
            <div id="queue" class="queue"></div>
        </div>

        <div id="controlPanel">
            <input type="number" id="priorityInput" placeholder="Priority" min="1" max="100">
            <button id="addButton">Add Item</button>
            <button id="removeButton">Remove Highest Priority</button>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        const queue = [];
        const queueElement = document.getElementById('queue');

        document.getElementById('addButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
            const priority = parseInt(document.getElementById('priorityInput').value);
            if (!isNaN(priority) && priority > 0) {
                const item = { priority: priority };
                queue.push(item);
                queue.sort((a, b) => b.priority - a.priority); // Sort in descending order by priority
                renderQueue();
                document.getElementById('priorityInput').value = '';
            } else {
                alert("Please enter a valid priority number.");
            }
        });

        document.getElementById('removeButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
            if (queue.length > 0) {
                queue.shift(); // Remove the highest priority item
                renderQueue();
            } else {
                alert("Queue is empty.");
            }
        });

        function renderQueue() {
            queueElement.innerHTML = '';
            queue.forEach(item => {
                const itemDiv = document.createElement('div');
                itemDiv.className = 'item';
                itemDiv.textContent = `Priority: ${item.priority}`;
                itemDiv.style.transform = "translateY(0)";
                queueElement.appendChild(itemDiv);
            });
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation of the Design

#### Concept Title
**Understanding Priority Queue**

#### Learning Objective
After interacting with this module, users should understand how priority queues work by adding items with different priorities and observing how the queue maintains the order based on priority levels. They will also learn about removing the highest priority item.

#### Interaction Design
1. **Text Input**: Users enter a numeric value representing the priority of an item.
2. **Add Item Button**: When clicked, the item is added to a visual queue, which sorts and displays the items based on priority.
3. **Remove Highest Priority Button**: This button, when clicked, removes the highest priority item from the queue, providing immediate visual feedback on the queue state.
4. **Visual Feedback**: Items are displayed dynamically in a queue, with animations reflecting the order based on the priority level.
5. **Alert Messages**: Users receive alerts for invalid input or attempts to remove items from an empty queue.

#### Layout Description
- The entire layout is centered and responsive, with safe area margins of **24 px** on all sides.
- Text elements, control buttons, and the queue are organized vertically for clarity.
- The queue visualization is in a dedicated area for focus, with sufficient spacing (minimum **16 px**) between interactive elements for accessibility.
- Controls are placed at the bottom, easy for users to interact with after viewing the queue.

This design maintains a clean and user-friendly interface, reinforcing the learning of priority queues through interactive participation and immediate feedback.

