            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-between;
            margin-top: 16px;
        }
        .array-item {
            width: 18%;
            padding: 20px;
            text-align: center;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 4px;
            background-color: #e7e7e7;
            transition: background 0.3s;
        }
        .found {
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
        }
        .searching {
            background-color: #FFA500;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Linear Search</h1>
        <p><strong>Learning Objective:</strong> Understand how Linear Search works by visually interacting with an array of numbers.</p>

        <label for="numberInput">Enter a number to search:</label>
        <input type="number" id="numberInput" />
        <button class="button" id="searchButton">Search Array</button>

        <div class="array-container" id="arrayContainer"></div>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Create an array of numbers
        const numbers = [3, 5, 2, 9, 7, 10, 1, 4];

        // Display the numbers in the array
        const arrayContainer = document.getElementById('arrayContainer');
        numbers.forEach((num) => {
            const item = document.createElement('div');
            item.classList.add('array-item');
            item.innerText = num;
            arrayContainer.appendChild(item);
        });

        // Function for Linear Search
        function linearSearch(target) {
            const items = document.querySelectorAll('.array-item');
            for (let i = 0; i < numbers.length; i++) {
                items[i].classList.add('searching');

                // Simulating delay for visualization
                const delay = (i + 1) * 1000;
                setTimeout(() => {
                    if (numbers[i] === target) {
                        items[i].classList.add('found');
                    } else {
                        items[i].classList.remove('searching');
                    }
                }, delay);
            }
        }

        // Search button event listener
        document.getElementById('searchButton').addEventListener('click', () => {
            const target = parseInt(document.getElementById('numberInput').value);
            if (isNaN(target)) {
                alert('Please enter a valid number');
                return;
            }
            // Reset previous search state
            document.querySelectorAll('.array-item').forEach(item => {
                item.classList.remove('found', 'searching');
            });
            linearSearch(target);
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation of the Design Plan:

1. **Concept Title:** Linear Search

2. **Learning Objective:** After interacting with this module, users will understand how Linear Search traverses through an array to find a specified number and visualize the searching process.

3. **Interaction Design:**
   - Users enter a number in an input field and click the "Search Array" button.
   - Upon clicking the button, each array item animates to indicate that it is being examined.
   - If a match is found, the background color of the corresponding item changes to green (`found` class).
   - If the item is being searched, it changes to orange (`searching` class) to indicate active searching.
   - Visual feedback is provided through animations and color changes for clarity.

4. **Layout Description:**
   - The module is centered in the viewport with a clear, white background to enhance focus.
   - Input fields and buttons are stacked vertically, each separated by a minimum of 16 px for clarity.
   - The array items are displayed in a flex container, spaced evenly across the width, with 16 px margins between them.
   - Text and buttons maintain a margin of 24 px from the browser edges to ensure accessibility and good readability.
   - The design is responsive and adapts for smaller screens, ensuring that the educational experience remains effective across different devices.

This interactive module ensures an engaging and effective way for users to learn about Linear Search through hands-on experience.

Here’s a design plan for an interactive HTML page that explores the Merge Sort algorithm. The following sections outline the key components of the module:

### Interactive HTML Module Design for Merge Sort

---

#### Concept Title:
**Understanding Merge Sort: A Visual Guide**

---

#### Learning Objective:
Users will understand how the Merge Sort algorithm works through visual animation and interaction, allowing them to visualize the divide-and-conquer approach and observe how lists get sorted step-by-step.

---

#### Interaction Design:
1. **Interactive Controls:**
   - **Start Sort Button:** Users click this button to initiate the sorting process.
   - **Input Box:** Users can type in a series of numbers separated by commas (e.g., `38, 27, 43, 3, 9, 82, 10`). They can also click a "Generate Random Numbers" button to fill the input box with random numbers.
   - **Step Through Button:** A button allowing users to step through the sorting process one iteration at a time.
   - **Reset Button:** Resets the state to enable new inputs.

2. **Visual Responses:**
   - **Canvas Area:** A visual representation of the entered numbers as bars on a canvas. As the sort progresses, the heights of the bars animate to show the sorting action.
   - **Highlighting Elements:** The merging parts of the list will be highlighted to show which elements are being combined at each step.
   - **Sorted State:** A final animation that confirms the list is sorted by smoothing the transition to display the sorted bars.

---

#### Layout Description:

- **Overall Layout:**
  - Use a flexbox layout to center the content with a maximum width of 800px.
  - Safe margins of 24px will be maintained on all sides. Spacing of 16px will separate interactive elements.

- **Header:**
