- **Animation and Color Feedback:** Blocks change color during sorting, emphasizing action points and completed steps.
- **Clear Instructions and Feedback:** Textual instructions guide the user through each step of the sorting algorithm.

This design promotes an engaging and educational experience, allowing users to perceive Insertion Sort visually and interactively.

Here's a detailed design plan for an interactive HTML module that teaches the concept of Linear Search, along with a complete implementation.

### Interactive HTML Module Design: Linear Search

#### Concept Title:
**Linear Search Simulator**

#### Learning Objective:
Users will understand the concept of Linear Search by visualizing how the algorithm searches through an array for a target value. Users will interactively play with the input array and target value, observing how the algorithm processes each step of the search.

#### Interaction Design:
- **Array Input:** Users can customize the array of integers by adding values via a text input field and clicking an "Add" button. Users will also set one of these values as the target by clicking on it.
- **Search Action:** A "Search" button will initiate the search process. During this search:
  - The algorithm visually highlights the current index being checked.
  - If the target value is found, it highlights it in green and stops the search, displaying a message indicating success.
  - If the target isn’t found after checking all elements, it highlights all the elements in red after the search completes, displaying a failure message.

Animations or visual feedback will consist of a smooth highlight transition as the algorithm progresses through the elements.

#### Layout Description:
The layout will be responsive with a clean, organized appearance, maintaining clarity and focus. The following elements will be laid out within a safe area margin of 24 px on all sides:

1. **Title Section:** At the top-center of the page, displaying "Linear Search Simulator" in bold, large font.

2. **Array Input Section:**
   - A text input field for users to input numbers separated by commas (e.g., `5, 3, 7, 9`).
   - An "Add" button next to the input field.
   - A list beneath the input field displaying the current array values.

3. **Target Selection:**
   - Each number in the array will be clickable to set it as the target value, which is reflected next to the input field with a label "Target: [value]".

4. **Search Section:**
   - A "Search" button to start the search process.
   - A feedback area that will display messages such as "Element found!" or "Element not found!" below the search button.

5. **Visualization Area:**
   - A horizontal list to represent the array visually, with each value displayed as a colored box that will change colors based on the search status.

### Sample Implementation

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Linear Search Simulator</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            padding: 24px;
            box-sizing: border-box;
        }
        h1 {
            font-size: 2em;
            margin-bottom: 16px;
        }
        input {
            padding: 8px;
            margin-right: 16px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 8px 16px;
            margin-left: 16px;
        }
        .array-container {
            display: flex;
            margin: 16px 0;
            justify-content: center;
        }
        .box {
            width: 40px;
            height: 40px;
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            margin: 0 4px;
            border: 1px solid #000;
            transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
        }
        .highlight {
            background-color: yellow;
        }
        .found {
            background-color: green;
        }
        .not-found {
            background-color: red;
        }
        .feedback {
            margin-top: 16px;
            font-size: 1.2em;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Linear Search Simulator</h1>
    <div>
        <input type="text" id="arrayInput" placeholder="Enter numbers separated by commas" />
        <button onclick="addArray()">Add</button>
    </div>
    <div class="array-container" id="arrayDisplay"></div>

    <div>
        <h3 id="targetLabel">Target: None</h3>
        <button onclick="setTarget()">Set Target</button>
    </div>

    <button onclick="performSearch()">Search</button>

    <div class="feedback" id="feedback"></div>

    <script>
        let array = [];
        let target = null;

        function addArray() {
            const input = document.getElementById('arrayInput').value;
            array = input.split(',').map(num => parseInt(num.trim())).filter(num => !isNaN(num));

            displayArray();
        }

        function displayArray() {
            const arrayDisplay = document.getElementById('arrayDisplay');
            arrayDisplay.innerHTML = '';
            array.forEach((num, index) => {
                const box = document.createElement('div');
                box.innerText = num;
                box.className = 'box';
                box.onclick = () => setTargetValue(num);
                box.setAttribute('data-index', index);
                arrayDisplay.appendChild(box);
            });
        }

        function setTargetValue(num) {
            target = num;
            document.getElementById('targetLabel').innerText = `Target: ${target}`;
        }

        function performSearch() {
            if (target === null) {
                document.getElementById('feedback').innerText = "Please set a target value.";
                return;
            }
            const boxes = document.querySelectorAll('.box');
            let found = false;

            boxes.forEach((box, index) => {
                setTimeout(() => {
                    box.classList.add('highlight');
                    if (parseInt(box.innerText) === target) {
                        box.classList.add('found');
                        found = true;
                        document.getElementById('feedback').innerText = "Element found!";
                    } else if (index === boxes.length - 1 && !found) {
                        document.getElementById('feedback').innerText = "Element not found!";
                        boxes.forEach(box => box.classList.add('not-found'));
                    }
                }, 1000 * index);
            });
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation
- **User Input**: Users can enter an array and select a target value by clicking on the numbers.
- **Search Mechanism**: The search algorithm highlights the current item being checked and visually indicates whether the target was found or not.
- **Visual Feedback**: Background color changes provide clear visual feedback for the user's actions, reinforcing their understanding of the linear search process.

This self-contained module meets all the requirements and presents a practical, engaging way for users to learn about Linear Search interactively.

