Here's a comprehensive plan for an interactive HTML page that explains the concept of Longest Common Subsequence (LCS). 

### **Interactive HTML Module: Longest Common Subsequence**

---

### **Concept Title:**
Understanding Longest Common Subsequence (LCS)

---

### **Learning Objective:** 
By the end of this interactive module, users will understand the concept of Longest Common Subsequence, how to find it, and why it's important in string comparison, such as DNA sequence analysis and version control.

---

### **Interaction Design:**

1. **Input Boxes:** 
   - Users will input two strings in separate text fields.
   - Upon clicking a button, the program will calculate the LCS.

2. **Dynamic Visualization:**
   - After the computation, a visual representation will highlight the characters in both strings that are part of the LCS.
   - Use animations to smoothly transition from the input state to the result state.
   - Display the LCS result and the length of the LCS in an easy-to-read format.

3. **Feedback Mechanism:**
   - Provide messages after interaction (e.g., "LCS computed successfully", "Please input valid strings").
   - The color of the characters involved in the LCS will change, with an animation indicating selection.

---

### **Layout Description:**

- The layout will ensure a clean, minimal design centered on the concept being taught.

- **Header Section:** At the top, a large, bold title "Longest Common Subsequence" will catch the user's attention.

- **Input Section:** Below the header, two labeled input fields for users to enter their strings will be placed horizontally with adequate spacing. The labels will have a slight font size gradient for emphasis:
    - Input String 1: [___________]
    - Input String 2: [___________]

- **Action Area:** A button labeled "Find LCS" will be placed below the input fields for users to trigger the computation. It will have a distinct color for easy identification.

- **Result Section:** Below the action area, a visual panel will display the two input strings and highlight the characters of the LCS. This section will also show the computed LCS and its length.

- **Margins and Spacing:** The entire layout will maintain a safe area of 24px on all sides, with a minimum spacing of 16px between elements. All text will be easily readable with a font size no smaller than 16px.

- **Responsiveness:** The design will adapt to mobile view by stacking elements vertically and scaling down inputs and buttons accordingly.

### **HTML Implementation:**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Longest Common Subsequence</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            background-color: #f4f4f5;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            padding: 24px;
        }
        header {
            font-size: 2em;
            margin-bottom: 24px;
        }
        .input-area {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            margin-bottom: 16px;
        }
        label {
            margin: 0 8px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
        input {
            padding: 8px;
            margin: 0 16px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 4px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            font-size: 1em;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 4px;
            cursor: pointer;
            transition: background 0.3s;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        .result {
            margin-top: 24px;
            font-size: 1.2em;
            width: 100%;
            text-align: center;
        }
        .highlight {
            color: #ff5733;
            font-weight: bold;
            transition: color 0.3s;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<header>Longest Common Subsequence</header>

<div class="input-area">
    <label for="string1">Input String 1:</label>
    <input type="text" id="string1" placeholder="e.g., ABCDGH">
    <label for="string2">Input String 2:</label>
    <input type="text" id="string2" placeholder="e.g., AEDFHR">
</div>

<button id="findLCS">Find LCS</button>

<div class="result" id="result"></div>

<script>
    document.getElementById('findLCS').onclick = function() {
        const str1 = document.getElementById('string1').value;
        const str2 = document.getElementById('string2').value;
        const lcsResult = findLCS(str1, str2);
        displayResult(str1, str2, lcsResult);
    };

    function findLCS(str1, str2) {
        const dp = Array(str1.length + 1).fill(0).map(() => Array(str2.length + 1).fill(0));

        for (let i = 1; i <= str1.length; i++) {
            for (let j = 1; j <= str2.length; j++) {
                if (str1[i - 1] === str2[j - 1]) {
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1;
                } else {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1]);
                }
            }
        }

        return extractLCS(dp, str1, str2);
    }

    function extractLCS(dp, str1, str2) {
        let i = str1.length, j = str2.length;
        let lcs = '';

        while (i > 0 && j > 0) {
            if (str1[i - 1] === str2[j - 1]) {
                lcs = str1[i - 1] + lcs;
                i--;
                j--;
            } else if (dp[i - 1][j] > dp[i][j - 1]) {
                i--;
            } else {
                j--;
            }
        }
        return lcs;
    }

    function displayResult(str1, str2, lcsResult) {
        const resultDiv = document.getElementById('result');
        resultDiv.innerHTML = `
            String 1: <span>${highlightLCS(str1, lcsResult)}</span><br />
            String 2: <span>${highlightLCS(str2, lcsResult)}</span><br />
            LCS: ${lcsResult} (Length: ${lcsResult.length})
        `;
    }

    function highlightLCS(str, lcs) {
        let highlighted = '';
        let lcsIndex = 0;

        for (let char of str) {
            if (lcsIndex < lcs.length && char === lcs[lcsIndex]) {
                highlighted += `<span class="highlight">${char}</span>`;
                lcsIndex++;
            } else {
                highlighted += char;
            }
        }
        return highlighted;
    }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### **Explanation of Code:**

- **Header and Styles:** The code begins with a header and styles for appearance. It uses flexbox for alignment and ensures good spacing.

- **Input Logic:** Users can input two strings, and the "Find LCS" button triggers the logic.

- **LCS Calculation:** The LCS calculation uses dynamic programming to fill a matrix (`dp`) that leads to extracting the LCS.

- **Highlighting Mechanism:** When displaying the result, it highlights the characters in the LCS from both input strings.

- **Dynamic Interactivity:** All changes are reflected in real-time through DOM manipulation, with animations and visual feedback implemented directly in the CSS.

This module is self-contained, providing a clear understanding of the Longest Common Subsequence through interaction and visualization.

