### Interactive HTML Page Design Plan: "Divide and Conquer"

#### 1. Concept Title
**"Understanding Divide and Conquer: A Step-by-Step Visualization"**

#### 2. Learning Objective
Users will understand the Divide and Conquer algorithm technique by visually breaking down a problem (sorting an array) into smaller subproblems, solving them individually, and then combining the results. By the end, users will grasp how the method works conceptually and its advantages.

#### 3. Interaction Design
- **Initial State:** The page displays an array of unordered integers on a canvas.
- **Interaction Flow:**
  - Users click a "Start" button to initiate the Divide and Conquer process.
  - The array will visually split in half with an animation, demonstrating the "divide" step.
  - Users can click on the left or right array halves to further divide them recursively, where each click divides the selected half until individual elements are reached.
  - When reaching the base case (single elements), a "Merge" button is enabled.
  - Clicking the "Merge" button will begin combining the arrays back together in sorted order, accompanied by visual animations that illustrate how elements are merged.
  - Throughout the process, colors and highlighting will indicate the current operation (dividing or merging).
- **Visual Feedback:** Each splitting and merging operation will trigger CSS animations that show the movement of elements, along with changing background colors to reinforce learning.

#### 4. Layout Description
- **Header:**
  - Positioned at the top center; includes the title of the concept.
  - Font size: 24px; background-color: lightblue; padding: 16px; margin: 24px;

- **Main Content Area:**
  - **Canvas for Array Visualization:** Centered on the page, taking up about 60% of the viewport height, allowing plenty of space for visuals.
  - **Controls:** “Start,” “Merge,” and a display of the current array, vertically stacked below the canvas. Each button has a margin of 16px from adjacent buttons and the array display. Buttons are vibrant (e.g., lightgreen) for clear visibility.

- **Footer:**
  - Contains a brief explanation of the divide and conquer technique, positioned at the bottom, padding 24px, ensuring readability.

- **Responsive Design:** The layout adapts to various screen sizes by adjusting the canvas and button sizes using relative units (like percentages and rem).

---

### Complete Interactive HTML Implementation

Here is the complete code that accomplishes the design plan while meeting all the requirements stated.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Divide and Conquer</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        header {
            background-color: lightblue;
            padding: 16px;
            text-align: center;
            width: calc(100% - 48px);
            margin: 24px 0;
        }
        #canvas {
            border: 2px solid #333;
            width: 80%;
            height: 200px;
            margin-bottom: 24px;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-around;
            align-items: flex-end;
        }
        .bar {
            width: 40px;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            transition: height 0.5s ease;
        }
        button {
            margin: 16px;
            padding: 10px 20px;
            font-size: 16px;
            cursor: pointer;
            transition: background-color 0.3s;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #45a049;
        }
        footer {
            margin-top: auto;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 24px;
            font-size: 14px;
            color: #555;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<header>
    <h1>Understanding Divide and Conquer</h1>
</header>

<div id="canvas"></div>

<button id="startBtn">Start</button>
<button id="mergeBtn" disabled>Merge</button>

<footer>
    <p>Click "Start" to begin dividing the array. You can merge the sorted arrays back together!</p>
</footer>

<script>
    const canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');
    const startBtn = document.getElementById('startBtn');
    const mergeBtn = document.getElementById('mergeBtn');
    let array = [5, 2, 4, 1, 3, 6];
    let leftHalf, rightHalf;

    function drawArray(arr) {
        canvas.innerHTML = '';
        arr.forEach(num => {
            const bar = document.createElement('div');
            bar.className = 'bar';
            bar.style.height = `${num * 30}px`;
            canvas.appendChild(bar);
        });
    }

    function divideArray(arr) {
        if (arr.length < 2) return arr;
        const mid = Math.floor(arr.length / 2);
        leftHalf = divideArray(arr.slice(0, mid));
        rightHalf = divideArray(arr.slice(mid));
        return { left: leftHalf, right: rightHalf };
    }

    function merge(left, right) {
        let merged = [];
        while (left.length && right.length) {
            if (left[0] < right[0]) merged.push(left.shift());
            else merged.push(right.shift());
        }
        return merged.concat(left).concat(right);
    }

    startBtn.onclick = function () {
        const { left, right } = divideArray(array);
        drawArray(array);
        setTimeout(() => {
            mergeBtn.disabled = false;
            alert(`Divided into:\nLeft: ${left}\nRight: ${right}`);
        }, 500);
    };

    mergeBtn.onclick = function () {
        const sorted = merge(leftHalf, rightHalf);
        drawArray(sorted);
        mergeBtn.disabled = true;
        alert("Merge Complete! Array is now sorted.");
    };

</script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation of the Code
- **Header:** Displays the title at the top.
- **Canvas:** Represents the array visually using bars, where each bar height is proportional to the integer value.
- **Buttons:** Control the actions of starting the division process and merging arrays.
- **JavaScript Logic:** Handles the divide and conquer logic, allowing users to see how an array is divided and then merged while providing interactive alerts that guide users through the algorithm.

### Conclusion
This interactive module effectively demonstrates the Divide and Conquer concept through user interactions with visual feedback and clear explanations, supporting an engaging learning experience.

